  "text": "Source: [CITATION_1] The conventional interpretation of the 1920s is that these were the years of the 'doldrums' and in no way can be equated with trend growth, or low unemployment. However, this view has been challenged by a number of scholars that have explained the high level of unemployment as part of a supply-side problem 2 which as a general equilibrium issue have questioned the overvaluation of sterling on the return to gold in 1925 3 .",
